CARLOS MARQUES
MARCET: Thank you.

00:00:19.585 --> 00:00:21.960
FEMALE SPEAKER: He wanted to
share with you a funny story

00:00:21.960 --> 00:00:25.740
about shooting Google
and the bizarre fact

00:00:25.740 --> 00:00:26.890
that he's actually here.

00:00:26.890 --> 00:00:27.350
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
Well, it's

00:00:27.350 --> 00:00:28.474
actually a very long story.

00:00:28.474 --> 00:00:32.070
It's very weird to be in this
building, because, as you saw,

00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:35.960
that's a photograph of
this building in the movie,

00:00:35.960 --> 00:00:37.010
of the [INAUDIBLE].

00:00:37.010 --> 00:00:39.464
The funny thing is
when we were doing

00:00:39.464 --> 00:00:41.630
the script of the movie,
my photographer friend, who

00:00:41.630 --> 00:00:43.590
inspired the movie,
actually, he's a man,

00:00:43.590 --> 00:00:49.040
but I changed the gender--
he came to visit me.

00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:50.930
Then we decided, he read
the script and said,

00:00:50.930 --> 00:00:52.880
oh, this photographer
doesn't work like that.

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:55.046
I'll come through Los
Angeles, we'll make a project,

00:00:55.046 --> 00:00:59.770
we've got a grant from an
art institution and UCLA

00:00:59.770 --> 00:01:02.420
to help us and everything.

00:01:02.420 --> 00:01:06.450
We'll give you support so
you can make this art project

00:01:06.450 --> 00:01:07.450
before making the movie.

00:01:07.450 --> 00:01:11.040
So you have on one side the art
project, and on the other side

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:13.410
you have the movie, and
we'll use the art project

00:01:13.410 --> 00:01:15.070
to use it in the movie.

00:01:15.070 --> 00:01:16.662
The funny thing
is like, OK, so we

00:01:16.662 --> 00:01:17.870
started working on one thing.

00:01:17.870 --> 00:01:19.640
We shot on the
antennas, and then

00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:21.670
the antennas gave us
the idea, and then

00:01:21.670 --> 00:01:23.822
we shot the Google
building, but we

00:01:23.822 --> 00:01:26.280
didn't know it was Google at
the time, because like I said,

00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:28.071
when we took the picture,
it wasn't bought.

00:01:28.071 --> 00:01:30.140
And then the news came
on-- Google has bought,

00:01:30.140 --> 00:01:32.710
and it's like oh, somehow
it gave us the key to all.

00:01:32.710 --> 00:01:35.720
Maybe that's what the
photographic project needs

00:01:35.720 --> 00:01:39.530
to be, just randomly,
because it got bought.

00:01:39.530 --> 00:01:43.340
Then he's like, OK, we said
the thing about all the tools,

00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:45.240
you see the physicality
of internet.

00:01:45.240 --> 00:01:49.040
We all wonder, OK, internet,
but where is internet?

00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:51.830
Filmmakers, we shoot
things, we shoot things

00:01:51.830 --> 00:01:55.490
that you can touch, that you
can see, you don't shoot ideas.

00:01:55.490 --> 00:01:58.200
So it was like, how do
you shoot the internet?

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:00.210
Where is it?

00:02:00.210 --> 00:02:01.610
Where is it?

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:04.650
I want to see it.

00:02:04.650 --> 00:02:07.065
That wasn't where-- we were
trying to find this service

00:02:07.065 --> 00:02:07.690
and everything.

00:02:07.690 --> 00:02:10.300
But also Google
Maps, we're obsessed

00:02:10.300 --> 00:02:12.450
with Google Maps and this
thing that you can use

00:02:12.450 --> 00:02:15.490
to travel all around the world.

00:02:15.490 --> 00:02:18.500
It reminds me a lot of the
Lumiere brothers with the two

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:19.140
screens.

00:02:19.140 --> 00:02:22.315
The Lumiere brothers were the
first one doing films-- well,

00:02:22.315 --> 00:02:24.606
in America it was Edison,
but for the rest of the world

00:02:24.606 --> 00:02:25.439
it was the Lumieres.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:29.900
I love it.

00:02:29.900 --> 00:02:32.725
Basically, they do
panoramics of the world

00:02:32.725 --> 00:02:36.220
all around just to show
people how was Istanbul,

00:02:36.220 --> 00:02:40.750
how was this country they've
never seen before in France.

00:02:40.750 --> 00:02:41.590
It's like, woah.

00:02:41.590 --> 00:02:44.610
I feel nowadays Google
Maps makes the same thing.

00:02:44.610 --> 00:02:46.560
You just Google a
street view and you

00:02:46.560 --> 00:02:49.507
could have the same panoramic
view of anywhere in the world.

00:02:49.507 --> 00:02:51.340
Anyway, we were obsessed,
and it's like, OK,

00:02:51.340 --> 00:02:54.135
we have to photograph
the tools, and also,

00:02:54.135 --> 00:02:56.330
let's photograph the Google car.

00:02:56.330 --> 00:02:57.642
Then it was like, impossible.

00:02:57.642 --> 00:02:59.225
We got the [INAUDIBLE]
and everything,

00:02:59.225 --> 00:03:03.510
but how do you reach Google?

00:03:03.510 --> 00:03:07.750
It's seems very funny, but we
try any way, all the emails,

00:03:07.750 --> 00:03:10.960
all the contacts possible
through the university,

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:12.740
through something else.

00:03:12.740 --> 00:03:13.449
There was no way.

00:03:13.449 --> 00:03:15.489
We even came to-- not
these offices, because they

00:03:15.489 --> 00:03:17.580
were still in the other
offices in Santa Monica--

00:03:17.580 --> 00:03:18.670
we went there to the door.

00:03:18.670 --> 00:03:23.035
I'm trying to ask somebody,
knock on the [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:23.035 --> 00:03:24.140
Can we get in?

00:03:24.140 --> 00:03:26.165
We're not bad people,
we're not crazy people,

00:03:26.165 --> 00:03:27.540
we just want to
talk with Google.

00:03:30.390 --> 00:03:33.760
It was impossible
to talk with Google.

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:36.290
And then we decided, OK, you
cannot to talk with Google,

00:03:36.290 --> 00:03:38.500
Google talks with you.

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:43.560
That was actually what happened,
and now I'm in the building.

00:03:43.560 --> 00:03:48.050
But in a funny way, we decided,
OK, let's go to Silicon Valley,

00:03:48.050 --> 00:03:49.830
let's go to Google city.

00:03:49.830 --> 00:03:52.620
There's a place where Google is.

00:03:52.620 --> 00:03:55.875
We just went there, and we
looked for the Google car,

00:03:55.875 --> 00:03:58.340
and we found it in some corner.

00:03:58.340 --> 00:04:03.691
Then we just took the tripod,
took the picture, and went.

00:04:03.691 --> 00:04:05.440
Then it was funny,
because it was so hard,

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:07.023
but then when we
asked for permission,

00:04:07.023 --> 00:04:11.810
Google said, yeah,
fine, use the picture.

00:04:11.810 --> 00:04:12.870
Everything's fine.

00:04:12.870 --> 00:04:16.370
It's the weird structure
of the internet.

00:04:16.370 --> 00:04:20.560
There's no centers, you
really can't reach any center

00:04:20.560 --> 00:04:21.510
at any point.

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:23.480
It was very like
being in the castle,

00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:24.855
you know, a little
bit Kafka-ian.

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:29.680
It's funny, because that's
how all the artistic projects

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:32.890
started, because then we
were in Silicon Valley.

00:04:32.890 --> 00:04:34.900
For them it's like
the most strange place

00:04:34.900 --> 00:04:38.847
in the world, like very weird,
like all these buildings there.

00:04:38.847 --> 00:04:40.430
Then we start taking
all the pictures,

00:04:40.430 --> 00:04:42.910
and that's where all the
email at the end, she says,

00:04:42.910 --> 00:04:45.080
all the ideas came from.

00:04:45.080 --> 00:04:46.950
The funny thing,
we went to Yahoo

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:49.330
and we did the same thing,
we just took the tripod,

00:04:49.330 --> 00:04:52.720
went to this basket court
field-- court field, you say?

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:54.880
Yeah, I think-- with the
camera, took the picture,

00:04:54.880 --> 00:04:57.270
and left, with no
permission or anything.

00:04:57.270 --> 00:04:59.170
Then we say, OK
that's in the movie,

00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:00.930
so let's ask for permission.

00:05:00.930 --> 00:05:04.800
Then they said, oh, it's fine,
but this is the old logo.

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:10.290
Maybe you're can Photoshop
it and put the new logo.

00:05:10.290 --> 00:05:13.560
So that's basically what we did.

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:18.160
It was an experience to deal
with all of the new technology

00:05:18.160 --> 00:05:18.840
companies.

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:23.270
They have a different mentality
that still I don't understand,

00:05:23.270 --> 00:05:26.145
but it was kind of Kafka-ian.

