00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:45.360
Not doing it imposed,
but already shooting it,

00:11:45.360 --> 00:11:46.800
we were planning them.

00:11:46.800 --> 00:11:48.920
That's why we decided
to shoot with the EPIC.

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:51.211
The problem is that, for
example, for this first scene,

00:11:51.211 --> 00:11:53.230
we shot with the
lights-- you don't have

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:56.820
anywhere to hide the lights.

00:11:56.820 --> 00:12:01.020
You just basically
have to use windows.

00:12:01.020 --> 00:12:04.035
Dagmar, the DP, is she's
an amazing director

00:12:04.035 --> 00:12:06.630
of photography, and we
basically always think

00:12:06.630 --> 00:12:09.420
of lighting spaces.

00:12:09.420 --> 00:12:11.080
That's how we function.

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:13.900
We light the space and
I make the blocking

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:15.400
with the actors,
thinking already,

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:17.570
what's the possibilities
of the space?

00:12:17.570 --> 00:12:19.470
Basically, I use
the props, because I

00:12:19.470 --> 00:12:20.930
don't like to use marks.

00:12:20.930 --> 00:12:23.360
I don't like the act of
saying, you have to step.

00:12:23.360 --> 00:12:25.280
They can do it,
but to me, I just

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:27.920
want to be totally free
to be able to create.

00:12:27.920 --> 00:12:30.380
So I put, here is
the coffee pot,

00:12:30.380 --> 00:12:33.940
so I know he needs to his mark.

00:12:33.940 --> 00:12:36.720
The props are their marks.

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:39.670
Then we work with knowing
where the props are

00:12:39.670 --> 00:12:42.060
and where we're going
to put the lights.

00:12:42.060 --> 00:12:44.310
FEMALE SPEAKER: Do you like
Red cameras in particular?

00:12:44.310 --> 00:12:46.620
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
Yeah, I enjoy them a lot.

00:12:46.620 --> 00:12:49.320
Like a lot of the [INAUDIBLE]
before like [INAUDIBLE],

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:51.090
I like them a lot,
too, but there's

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:54.610
something about the Red, it
has its own specific colors

00:12:54.610 --> 00:12:56.230
and everything.

00:12:56.230 --> 00:12:58.270
I've really enjoyed
having the 4K.

00:13:01.332 --> 00:13:02.790
Some days it can
be very dangerous,

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:06.340
if you just use-- because
in cinema you have 4K now,

00:13:06.340 --> 00:13:09.350
so normally you end
up screening 2K.

00:13:09.350 --> 00:13:10.860
Basically, you can
do re-framings,

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:13.360
and move the camera.

00:13:13.360 --> 00:13:17.590
You can become a lazy filmmaker.

00:13:17.590 --> 00:13:24.850
But if you plan it well, and
if you think of it in a way

00:13:24.850 --> 00:13:26.620
that this is part
of your language,

00:13:26.620 --> 00:13:32.310
not as something you do as a
way of trying to solve problems,

00:13:32.310 --> 00:13:35.335
as a way of a
creative tool, I think

00:13:35.335 --> 00:13:36.784
it has a lot of possibilities.

00:13:36.784 --> 00:13:38.700
FEMALE SPEAKER: I hear
the Red's fairly heavy.

00:13:38.700 --> 00:13:42.670
Did you use it like-- is it a
gyro stabilizer for the walking

00:13:42.670 --> 00:13:43.920
shot or the movement shots?

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:46.170
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET: It's
all in tripod, some tripod

00:13:46.170 --> 00:13:47.465
and with all machine.

00:13:47.465 --> 00:13:50.290
It's all very big.

00:13:50.290 --> 00:13:55.030
Some people use Steadicams as
a way to substitute a dolly,

00:13:55.030 --> 00:13:57.820
but it's not the same.

00:13:57.820 --> 00:13:59.870
There's actually
very few filmmakers

00:13:59.870 --> 00:14:03.220
who know how to use Steadicam.

00:14:03.220 --> 00:14:06.740
A lot of times it's
an easy tool to use,

00:14:06.740 --> 00:14:10.240
but to me the problem was,
because it makes your life much

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:12.720
easier, for us it would
have been much easier

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:14.304
to go with a Steadicam
here and there.

00:14:14.304 --> 00:14:15.761
But the problem
with the Steadicams

00:14:15.761 --> 00:14:17.270
is that they are
called Steadicams,

00:14:17.270 --> 00:14:19.430
but they never stay steady.

00:14:19.430 --> 00:14:21.720
They always have
these things that

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:24.050
are floating and everything.

00:14:24.050 --> 00:14:27.720
For us it was important to
stay at the moment with them,

00:14:27.720 --> 00:14:31.920
so we used these old
machines like in the 1940s

00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:33.950
with the smaller cameras.

00:14:33.950 --> 00:14:34.710
It's beautiful.

00:14:34.710 --> 00:14:38.520
There's something-- you
see like Douglas they may

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:40.950
be starting even huge cameras.

00:14:40.950 --> 00:14:42.830
Now they are small.

00:14:42.830 --> 00:14:47.410
You can feel the weight of the
[GROAN], Gone with the Wind,

00:14:47.410 --> 00:14:48.780
and then it's like, woah.

00:14:48.780 --> 00:14:51.050
There's something about
that is very beautiful,

00:14:51.050 --> 00:14:55.000
I feel, of being on the ground.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.410
FEMALE SPEAKER: I also read
that you said that you don't

00:14:57.410 --> 00:14:59.130
choose a movie, it chooses you.

00:14:59.130 --> 00:15:02.480
So I feel like sometimes,
when you're in a relationship,

00:15:02.480 --> 00:15:04.250
there's a moment
where you're like,

00:15:04.250 --> 00:15:06.940
that was when I fell
in love with him.

00:15:06.940 --> 00:15:09.919
Was there a moment when
this movie chose you?

00:15:09.919 --> 00:15:11.835
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
That's a good question.

00:15:14.910 --> 00:15:18.640
There's a first moment
where it makes it click .

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:20.650
That normally
happened when I have

00:15:20.650 --> 00:15:23.900
ideas for movies and with
shows before, and everything.

00:15:23.900 --> 00:15:27.510
I have this idea floating,
this other idea floating,

00:15:27.510 --> 00:15:29.490
and then suddenly it
just makes that click.

00:15:29.490 --> 00:15:33.890
In that case, it was
oh, there's internet.

00:15:33.890 --> 00:15:35.495
I wanted to explore
all the language

00:15:35.495 --> 00:15:39.290
of long-distance relationships,
the language of webcams

00:15:39.290 --> 00:15:41.080
and screens.

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:45.344
Then my friend [INAUDIBLE] the
photographer, came to visit me,

00:15:45.344 --> 00:15:47.010
and then he told me
click, click, click.

00:15:47.010 --> 00:15:49.000
Oh, yes, a photographer
coming to Los Angeles,

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.030
and then it's like,
boom, they are born.

00:15:51.030 --> 00:15:52.690
There's a spark
that goes in there,

00:15:52.690 --> 00:15:54.690
and then it's like,
OK, that's an idea.

00:15:54.690 --> 00:15:58.490
It that grabs you and
it doesn't leave you.

00:15:58.490 --> 00:16:02.160
I think it's almost
like first sight love.

00:16:02.160 --> 00:16:05.337
It's mostly that afterwards
you cannot hate it.

00:16:05.337 --> 00:16:07.420
In a relationship, you
fall in love at the moment,

00:16:07.420 --> 00:16:09.190
and then you're
seven years together,

00:16:09.190 --> 00:16:12.150
and then there's
no sex or anything.

00:16:12.150 --> 00:16:16.890
Then you have to fall in
love again, and go to dinner,

00:16:16.890 --> 00:16:18.350
and then you can fall in love.

00:16:18.350 --> 00:16:21.960
It's mostly like pre-falling
in love again and again.

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:24.460
FEMALE SPEAKER: You said that
the last scene was emotionally

00:16:24.460 --> 00:16:26.010
challenging for you.

00:16:26.010 --> 00:16:27.200
I wanted to know why.

00:16:30.110 --> 00:16:32.870
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
I guess, of course,

00:16:32.870 --> 00:16:34.950
there's a personal
part on the story,

00:16:34.950 --> 00:16:36.590
but I haven't lived exactly.

00:16:36.590 --> 00:16:38.190
I've never gone
to a door, nobody

00:16:38.190 --> 00:16:39.890
has ever come to my door.

00:16:39.890 --> 00:16:41.740
But there was something
about this material

00:16:41.740 --> 00:16:44.160
of just showing the breakup.

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:47.360
Somehow, when they ask me if
this movie is autobiographical,

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:49.930
it is, and it is not,
in many ways, but maybe

00:16:49.930 --> 00:16:53.830
it sums up all my
failed relationships.

00:16:53.830 --> 00:17:00.700
Somehow, it was trying to
confront what happens when you

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:04.460
still love somebody but you
know that you cannot live a life

00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:08.240
together, and trying to really
go deep into this moment

00:17:08.240 --> 00:17:09.349
and not planning.

00:17:09.349 --> 00:17:13.440
I was very concerned
about going into the scene

00:17:13.440 --> 00:17:16.609
with very pre-formed ideas.

00:17:16.609 --> 00:17:19.069
I wanted to be vulnerable,
me as the director,

00:17:19.069 --> 00:17:23.740
too, not really knowing
what needs to be.

00:17:23.740 --> 00:17:27.680
I know what they want to
capture, but I don't know how.

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:31.480
It was very funny, actually, in
the rehearsals with the actors,

00:17:31.480 --> 00:17:35.550
they always explain the
story, because I normally

00:17:35.550 --> 00:17:40.140
record the rehearsals, but this
time I just left them alone.

00:17:40.140 --> 00:17:41.950
They were having
sex and they'd turn,

00:17:41.950 --> 00:17:43.325
it's like, where
is the director?

00:17:48.184 --> 00:17:49.600
But then when
you're sad, you have

00:17:49.600 --> 00:17:52.220
to be-- I think it
was Herzog who said,

00:17:52.220 --> 00:17:55.130
a director can never cry
on set, and it's true.

00:17:55.130 --> 00:17:59.080
You have to be very cold-minded
and be able to analyze,

00:17:59.080 --> 00:18:00.580
just guide the
actors and tell them,

00:18:00.580 --> 00:18:02.620
this is not working
here or there.

00:18:02.620 --> 00:18:06.000
This is happening, you have
to be almost scientific there

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.610
while also
corresponding and being

00:18:08.610 --> 00:18:12.870
sympathetic to their feelings,
but being able to analyze them.

00:18:12.870 --> 00:18:16.280
I was very afraid to have to do
both things at the same time,

00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:18.080
being able to have
both your right

00:18:18.080 --> 00:18:20.980
and left sides of
the brain connected

00:18:20.980 --> 00:18:23.840
and the same then confront
them in a way that

00:18:23.840 --> 00:18:25.190
is the ending of your movie.

00:18:25.190 --> 00:18:27.160
Actually we didn't shoot
it until-- the night

00:18:27.160 --> 00:18:30.469
before, I was watching movies,
like sex scenes and everything,

00:18:30.469 --> 00:18:33.010
maybe they have a solution, but
of course, it was all stupid.

00:18:33.010 --> 00:18:38.630
But then, I didn't shoot it
until the last shot, almost.

00:18:38.630 --> 00:18:42.770
I guess I was looking for this
magic to happen where, oh yeah,

00:18:42.770 --> 00:18:43.530
it's cut.

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:46.500
It's right in the moment
when the sun is coming out,

00:18:46.500 --> 00:18:48.760
the [INAUDIBLE] is
going to get married,

00:18:48.760 --> 00:18:51.770
the taxi's on the floor,
she's missing her plane.

00:18:51.770 --> 00:18:54.610
These dramatic moments
of them happened.

00:18:54.610 --> 00:18:55.744
It gives you a rush.

00:18:55.744 --> 00:18:57.410
At the end, I feel
like if we make them,

00:18:57.410 --> 00:19:00.200
we make movies for the
pleasure of making them

00:19:00.200 --> 00:19:03.000
into these little flash moments.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:05.160
I guess it was a way
of pushing myself

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:07.300
into this limited situation.

00:19:07.300 --> 00:19:09.710
Of course, I'm not doing
like "Fitzcarraldo."

00:19:09.710 --> 00:19:13.360
I'm not sending a
boat over a mountain,

00:19:13.360 --> 00:19:16.610
but still, you're
looking for this moment

00:19:16.610 --> 00:19:19.540
where something magical,
some kind of truth happens,

00:19:19.540 --> 00:19:23.500
or you feel that
happens for yourself.

00:19:23.500 --> 00:19:26.000
FEMALE SPEAKER: If that was
the most challenging part

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:27.880
of the movie, emotionally,
what was probably

00:19:27.880 --> 00:19:32.440
the most fun or most awesome
moment for you in the movie?

00:19:32.440 --> 00:19:34.690
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET: There
was a lot of fun moments.

00:19:34.690 --> 00:19:37.810
From the moment where they
are trying to throw things

00:19:37.810 --> 00:19:41.230
at one another, and
then when it happened,

00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:42.750
we tried so many times.

00:19:42.750 --> 00:19:44.520
Every time was fun.

00:19:44.520 --> 00:19:47.790
I do a lot the takes so
we tried to make it funny.

00:19:47.790 --> 00:19:51.010
Then when it happened, we all
look at each other, like, woah,

00:19:51.010 --> 00:19:52.530
it looked like it went through.

00:19:55.860 --> 00:19:57.700
The first scene
was a lot of fun,

00:19:57.700 --> 00:20:01.510
because it's like
a choreography.

00:20:01.510 --> 00:20:04.590
It gives you also
a rush because it's

00:20:04.590 --> 00:20:08.000
like, OK, you're getting closer
to the time, but you know,

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.990
it still is like 20 minutes.

00:20:10.990 --> 00:20:15.740
Everything needs to be perfect,
and when it happens, go crazy,

00:20:15.740 --> 00:20:16.740
and we shout.

00:20:16.740 --> 00:20:19.020
It seems like it was
the end of the world,

00:20:19.020 --> 00:20:22.409
hugging everybody, oh, sad.

00:20:22.409 --> 00:20:23.450
It was something special.

00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:25.459
It was fun to shoot.

00:20:25.459 --> 00:20:26.875
FEMALE SPEAKER: I
want to read you

00:20:26.875 --> 00:20:30.460
a quote I read that you wrote.

00:20:30.460 --> 00:20:31.480
I hope you don't mind.

00:20:31.480 --> 00:20:32.610
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET: No,
you're very well-prepared.

00:20:32.610 --> 00:20:34.494
You're probably the
best-prepared interview

00:20:34.494 --> 00:20:35.530
I've had.

00:20:35.530 --> 00:20:38.740
FEMALE SPEAKER: You wrote, "It's
a problem with our generation:

00:20:38.740 --> 00:20:40.620
it's difficult to
plan for the future,

00:20:40.620 --> 00:20:42.610
not just because of
the financial crisis,

00:20:42.610 --> 00:20:44.790
but also because
of hedonism, which

00:20:44.790 --> 00:20:47.000
is the antithesis of sacrifice.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:50.710
And this whole debate on what
self-sacrifice means is also

00:20:50.710 --> 00:20:51.610
very interesting."

00:20:51.610 --> 00:20:55.750
I think I quote you
from March, 2014.

00:20:55.750 --> 00:20:57.730
I wanted to ask you,
in that statement,

00:20:57.730 --> 00:20:59.580
are you talking
about our generation

00:20:59.580 --> 00:21:04.660
being more self-orientated and
losing a sense of community?

00:21:04.660 --> 00:21:12.290
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
Yeah, I wouldn't

00:21:12.290 --> 00:21:15.990
want to fall into cliches
of yeah, just [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:15.990 --> 00:21:17.110
and everything.

00:21:17.110 --> 00:21:19.600
I feel somehow it's a
liberation, also, in many ways,

00:21:19.600 --> 00:21:22.610
of some rules that we narrate.

00:21:22.610 --> 00:21:27.440
The weight of tradition has
been the rule of society,

00:21:27.440 --> 00:21:30.870
like most of societies until
now that sentence so fast.

00:21:30.870 --> 00:21:35.550
I feel you have a family,
have to have kids,

00:21:35.550 --> 00:21:40.390
the woman is at home,
the husband goes to work.

00:21:40.390 --> 00:21:41.930
If you're high-class,
nobody works,

00:21:41.930 --> 00:21:45.267
you just live off of
the money of the others.

00:21:45.267 --> 00:21:45.850
So it's great.

00:21:48.980 --> 00:21:53.120
But it was very clear,
and then suddenly, there's

00:21:53.120 --> 00:21:55.775
this discourse of
authenticity that in some ways

00:21:55.775 --> 00:21:57.730
is very nice,
because you just try

00:21:57.730 --> 00:22:00.400
to find whatever
makes you happy,

00:22:00.400 --> 00:22:03.470
and there's no way, no rule.

00:22:03.470 --> 00:22:07.190
But that makes it also
very hard to-- there's

00:22:07.190 --> 00:22:12.020
a discourse of finding
yourself that also sometimes

00:22:12.020 --> 00:22:16.130
can be very distracting from
the things that you really need.

00:22:16.130 --> 00:22:18.440
It's a contradiction
sometimes, because trying

00:22:18.440 --> 00:22:20.590
to find yourself,
you're not yourself

00:22:20.590 --> 00:22:23.410
if it's not compared
to other people,

00:22:23.410 --> 00:22:25.340
in a framing of other people.

00:22:25.340 --> 00:22:27.730
We sometimes forget that
this philosopher who

00:22:27.730 --> 00:22:32.130
wrote a whole book about it,
basically talking-- we all

00:22:32.130 --> 00:22:34.230
need to be special nowadays, no?

00:22:34.230 --> 00:22:39.720
And you can be the guy who has
like 14,322 hairs on your head.

00:22:39.720 --> 00:22:43.570
But what does that mean?

00:22:43.570 --> 00:22:46.830
Does it mean anything
for somebody else?

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:49.340
I feel there's something in
this idea of-- in building

00:22:49.340 --> 00:22:51.570
relationships, a lot
of things sometimes

00:22:51.570 --> 00:22:53.620
happen and the thing
is just like, oh yeah,

00:22:53.620 --> 00:22:56.000
professional life
against-- I wanted

00:22:56.000 --> 00:22:59.600
to be made aware of that, of
professional schools, family,

00:22:59.600 --> 00:23:01.460
and [INAUDIBLE].

00:23:01.460 --> 00:23:04.540
It's more like, there's
no one route now,

00:23:04.540 --> 00:23:08.380
so now it's really hard to
find somebody who you can

00:23:08.380 --> 00:23:10.970
partner for a long, long time.

00:23:10.970 --> 00:23:12.625
That's a choice,
not an obligation.

00:23:15.490 --> 00:23:17.400
I think the sacrifice
thing-- it's funny,

00:23:17.400 --> 00:23:20.330
I had to cut a bunch of
the dialogue of the movie

00:23:20.330 --> 00:23:21.950
because I think it
was too explicit,

00:23:21.950 --> 00:23:23.699
but there was a moment
in the ending scene

00:23:23.699 --> 00:23:28.770
where he was telling her, we
don't know how to sacrifice.

00:23:28.770 --> 00:23:31.260
We're a generation
where we don't know.

00:23:31.260 --> 00:23:34.350
Then she said, oh, my
parents did sacrifice,

00:23:34.350 --> 00:23:36.540
and it didn't work out
very well for them.

00:23:36.540 --> 00:23:38.020
So that true.

00:23:38.020 --> 00:23:40.200
There's both sides of sacrifice.

00:23:40.200 --> 00:23:44.980
It shouldn't feel--
sacrifice if not-- it's

00:23:44.980 --> 00:23:49.300
a dangerous line in
that relationship.

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:51.980
You have to put effort,
and what this effort

00:23:51.980 --> 00:23:55.290
means, because then we
start to basically go

00:23:55.290 --> 00:23:59.190
to think in the relationship,
oh, is it worth it?

00:23:59.190 --> 00:24:02.820
Should I invest so much
effort in this relationship?

00:24:02.820 --> 00:24:06.750
The outcome is not-- so we start
to enter with the mentality

00:24:06.750 --> 00:24:11.550
that it's not about an outcome,
it's love, you give it,

00:24:11.550 --> 00:24:14.640
and maybe you return, maybe not.

00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:18.430
I think it's dangerous to
get into those channels,

00:24:18.430 --> 00:24:22.729
and sacrifice is something
you do expecting nothing.

00:24:22.729 --> 00:24:25.270
But at the same time, there's
a connotation that [INAUDIBLE].

00:24:27.860 --> 00:24:30.220
Catholic kind of
connotation is horrible.

00:24:30.220 --> 00:24:32.550
As a Catholic, I say it.

00:24:32.550 --> 00:24:37.450
I'm not practicing, but,
[INAUDIBLE] Catholic, I guess.

00:24:37.450 --> 00:24:39.430
FEMALE SPEAKER: Do you
have a dream project

00:24:39.430 --> 00:24:41.540
that you would love
to make one day?

00:24:41.540 --> 00:24:43.550
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
A dream project?

00:24:43.550 --> 00:24:45.130
Wow.

00:24:45.130 --> 00:24:47.750
It's very hard to say,
because to me, things

00:24:47.750 --> 00:24:50.740
go very one to another.

00:24:50.740 --> 00:24:53.290
If they had asked
me 10 years ago,

00:24:53.290 --> 00:24:55.410
I would never have
said I had done

00:24:55.410 --> 00:24:56.690
the movie like the one I did.

00:25:00.220 --> 00:25:03.670
Just supposing that I'm
going to be something

00:25:03.670 --> 00:25:06.730
that I am now in
10 years, and that

00:25:06.730 --> 00:25:09.400
would be most
horrible thing if I'm

00:25:09.400 --> 00:25:11.960
the same person in 10 years.

00:25:11.960 --> 00:25:14.180
It's really hard to think.

00:25:14.180 --> 00:25:17.830
I guess doing
something meaningful,

00:25:17.830 --> 00:25:21.520
but there's always
ideas and projects,

00:25:21.520 --> 00:25:24.740
but something that I
like at some moment,

00:25:24.740 --> 00:25:28.160
then you don't have it anymore.

00:25:28.160 --> 00:25:32.340
This is very hard because
ideas change for me.

00:25:32.340 --> 00:25:36.270
I would love my project
will be making movies

00:25:36.270 --> 00:25:41.722
until I'm 105 years old,
like Manoel de Oliveira.

00:25:41.722 --> 00:25:44.180
I like his movies, I'm not a
super fan, but if they ask me,

00:25:44.180 --> 00:25:45.721
which filmmaker
would you like to be?

00:25:45.721 --> 00:25:47.040
It's him.

00:25:47.040 --> 00:25:50.380
105 and making movies,
what else do you want?

00:25:50.380 --> 00:25:52.370
FEMALE SPEAKER: Do you
have a purpose in life,

00:25:52.370 --> 00:25:55.020
and do you think you're
going to fulfill that purpose

00:25:55.020 --> 00:25:57.036
unless you're making a movie?

00:25:57.036 --> 00:25:58.994
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
I know I'm going to die.

00:25:58.994 --> 00:26:00.730
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:02.425 --> 00:26:04.924
FEMALE SPEAKER: Is there a
story you really want to tell?

00:26:06.737 --> 00:26:08.320
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
I guess I don't

00:26:08.320 --> 00:26:09.986
want to think too
much, because then you

00:26:09.986 --> 00:26:11.860
start to get, oh,
yeah, I'm an author,

00:26:11.860 --> 00:26:15.220
or, that's my discourse
about the world,

00:26:15.220 --> 00:26:17.490
and I should be talking
about these things.

00:26:17.490 --> 00:26:20.290
I prefer just to think about
the things that really worry me,

00:26:20.290 --> 00:26:22.570
and what are the things
that really move me now,

00:26:22.570 --> 00:26:26.080
and be with my
instinct at the moment.

00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:29.560
Because if not, I can
get very egocentric.

00:26:29.560 --> 00:26:32.460
Your ego-- your ego is
just a part of yourself.

00:26:32.460 --> 00:26:34.820
You have many more other
parts, much more interesting.

00:26:38.350 --> 00:26:41.870
Right now I'm interested in
investigating the relationships

00:26:41.870 --> 00:26:44.440
of how we're changing nowadays.

00:26:44.440 --> 00:26:49.430
There's this French
saying, [INAUDIBLE],

00:26:49.430 --> 00:26:53.630
the real is painted as you
see it, being of your time.

00:26:53.630 --> 00:26:57.770
That, to me, was right
now, it's important

00:26:57.770 --> 00:27:01.290
trying to investigate
what's happening around me.

00:27:01.290 --> 00:27:04.710
Making films, to me,
is a way to really

00:27:04.710 --> 00:27:07.730
be able to-- the
luxury to investigate

00:27:07.730 --> 00:27:10.455
and also re-create how you feel.

00:27:14.270 --> 00:27:16.530
It's a luxurious job.

00:27:16.530 --> 00:27:18.500
I'm still weird when
I say, oh are you

00:27:18.500 --> 00:27:20.230
going to pay me to do this job?

00:27:20.230 --> 00:27:21.759
Really?

00:27:21.759 --> 00:27:24.050
It's great, but sometimes it
feels like a blessing more

00:27:24.050 --> 00:27:27.800
than a job.

00:27:27.800 --> 00:27:31.310
FEMALE SPEAKER: Does anybody
have a question for Carlos?

00:27:31.310 --> 00:27:32.143
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:27:33.125 --> 00:27:39.110
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
in the movie

00:27:39.110 --> 00:27:43.090
they have a long-distance
relationship, but in general,

00:27:43.090 --> 00:27:46.750
do you think that
technology actually

00:27:46.750 --> 00:27:52.421
helps people get closer, or
are they doing the opposite?

00:27:52.421 --> 00:27:54.420
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
No, it's a good question.

00:27:54.420 --> 00:27:57.800
I don't have answer for it.

00:27:57.800 --> 00:28:00.975
Somehow the movie offers
more questions than answers.

00:28:00.975 --> 00:28:02.250
That's true.

00:28:02.250 --> 00:28:04.530
I think technology is like
anything, how you use it.

00:28:04.530 --> 00:28:07.090
It's like, atomic
energy, is it good?

00:28:07.090 --> 00:28:09.780
Depends.

00:28:09.780 --> 00:28:11.880
I think the same thing,
it can bring you closer,

00:28:11.880 --> 00:28:14.390
but at the same time, it
can bring you farther away,

00:28:14.390 --> 00:28:16.590
because of the feeling
that you are close,

00:28:16.590 --> 00:28:19.880
but you live without being
aware of the things that you're

00:28:19.880 --> 00:28:21.040
missing.

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:24.070
You think that just having a
computer, you know somebody,

00:28:24.070 --> 00:28:26.280
that you can talk
everyday, and pretend

00:28:26.280 --> 00:28:28.280
that you could have just
a normal, everyday life

00:28:28.280 --> 00:28:30.390
with somebody that is so far.

00:28:30.390 --> 00:28:33.310
That can harm a lot
of relationships,

00:28:33.310 --> 00:28:36.580
because at the end,
physicality and presence

00:28:36.580 --> 00:28:39.100
is such an important
part of a relationship.

00:28:39.100 --> 00:28:41.255
At the same time,
it can keep you

00:28:41.255 --> 00:28:43.750
in contact with many people.

00:28:43.750 --> 00:28:47.040
I always say the same,
but I talk more sometimes

00:28:47.040 --> 00:28:49.600
with my parents when I'm
abroad then when I'm home.

00:28:49.600 --> 00:28:53.230
When I'm home, you go
to dinner on Sundays,

00:28:53.230 --> 00:28:57.030
it a bunch of family people,
and you don't say anything.

00:28:57.030 --> 00:28:59.220
Then when you're in
front of a computer,

00:28:59.220 --> 00:29:00.290
then you have to talk.

00:29:00.290 --> 00:29:04.070
Then, woah, you talk about
many things I never expected.

00:29:04.070 --> 00:29:06.570
I will have talks with them.

00:29:06.570 --> 00:29:09.800
It all depends on the situation.

00:29:09.800 --> 00:29:13.400
What is important is to see
what we lose and what we win,

00:29:13.400 --> 00:29:15.440
and try to use them
the best way possible.

00:29:20.750 --> 00:29:21.320
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:29:21.320 --> 00:29:23.650
First, I wanted to thank you
for coming here and making

00:29:23.650 --> 00:29:24.540
this film.

00:29:24.540 --> 00:29:26.790
I've gone through a long
distance relationship myself,

00:29:26.790 --> 00:29:30.240
so some of the stuff is
very resonate with me.

00:29:30.240 --> 00:29:32.780
I just want to say
that I really like

00:29:32.780 --> 00:29:34.920
the song you chose,
the Magnetic Fields

00:29:34.920 --> 00:29:37.570
song "Nothing Matters When
We're Dancing" for the movie.

00:29:37.570 --> 00:29:41.950
I thought it was used very
well knitting the two scenes.

00:29:41.950 --> 00:29:44.120
How did you choose that song?

00:29:44.120 --> 00:29:45.620
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
It's probably

00:29:45.620 --> 00:29:47.700
one of the very few
things that's still there

00:29:47.700 --> 00:29:49.990
from the very first
draft of the movie.

00:29:49.990 --> 00:29:53.380
It actually was
there all the time.

00:29:53.380 --> 00:29:55.080
At the time, coming
through Los Angeles,

00:29:55.080 --> 00:29:56.610
that's when I
started writing this,

00:29:56.610 --> 00:29:58.800
almost like seven years ago.

00:29:58.800 --> 00:30:04.940
I was very much rediscovering
The Magnetic Fields,

00:30:04.940 --> 00:30:08.260
and listening again,
the song was like, wow,

00:30:08.260 --> 00:30:13.700
there's something
about-- Stephin Merritt

00:30:13.700 --> 00:30:17.160
has this ability to write
these lyrics in a way that

00:30:17.160 --> 00:30:19.130
is almost cheesy, but it's not.

00:30:22.400 --> 00:30:26.430
It feels the feelings,
but with a certain irony

00:30:26.430 --> 00:30:28.530
that is not sarcastic.

00:30:28.530 --> 00:30:30.540
That was the tone for me.

00:30:30.540 --> 00:30:35.560
I wanted to use some irony, but
I didn't want a distant irony.

00:30:35.560 --> 00:30:38.130
I wanted to be close
to the characters

00:30:38.130 --> 00:30:39.870
be able to explore feelings.

00:30:39.870 --> 00:30:44.280
Of course, there was also
a part of the lyrics that

00:30:44.280 --> 00:30:46.750
has to do with
dancing, and dancing

00:30:46.750 --> 00:30:48.660
is something you
can only do when

00:30:48.660 --> 00:30:50.850
you are in front of each other.

00:30:50.850 --> 00:30:53.450
Then, through the song,
the idea of the scene

00:30:53.450 --> 00:30:56.830
came on, of them dancing
with the computers.

00:30:56.830 --> 00:30:59.820
So it's OK, nothing
happens when we're dancing,

00:30:59.820 --> 00:31:02.184
but what happens when
we are not dancing?

00:31:02.184 --> 00:31:03.600
That was a little
bit of the idea,

00:31:03.600 --> 00:31:05.642
almost, that I started
the movie with.

00:31:11.059 --> 00:31:11.850
AUDIENCE: Hi there.

00:31:11.850 --> 00:31:12.330
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET: Hi.

00:31:12.330 --> 00:31:14.060
AUDIENCE: Thanks for
bringing us the movie.

00:31:14.060 --> 00:31:14.310
CARLOS MARQUES
MARCET: Thank you.

00:31:14.310 --> 00:31:15.660
AUDIENCE: It's a beautiful film.

00:31:15.660 --> 00:31:17.410
I wanted to talk to
you about the editing.

00:31:17.410 --> 00:31:20.410
You have a lot of long
takes at the beginning,

00:31:20.410 --> 00:31:23.500
and I love editing.

00:31:23.500 --> 00:31:28.600
At one point Robert Wise
said that, as an editor, when

00:31:28.600 --> 00:31:30.850
he became a director, he
found that he was shooting

00:31:30.850 --> 00:31:32.557
more coverage, not less.

00:31:32.557 --> 00:31:34.723
At the beginning of the
film and throughout the film

00:31:34.723 --> 00:31:37.290
you have some really
long takes, which

00:31:37.290 --> 00:31:40.930
also seem to parallel
the video conference,

00:31:40.930 --> 00:31:43.180
because you really don't
have another take when you're

00:31:43.180 --> 00:31:44.900
video conferencing with people.

00:31:44.900 --> 00:31:46.780
How much of that
thought came in for you

00:31:46.780 --> 00:31:49.180
about what were shooting?

00:31:49.180 --> 00:31:52.210
Did you feel as an editor
that you wanted more coverage?

00:31:52.210 --> 00:31:55.300
Did you intentionally
go for the longer takes?

00:31:55.300 --> 00:31:57.000
Did the Red camera
help that because you

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.240
didn't have an end
of a reel coming

00:31:59.240 --> 00:32:01.350
and I'm running out of film?

00:32:01.350 --> 00:32:04.570
How did that affect you, and
what was your plan with these?

00:32:04.570 --> 00:32:06.070
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
I didn't know

00:32:06.070 --> 00:32:10.080
that he-- that's a quote from
Robert Wise, that he shot more?

00:32:10.080 --> 00:32:11.200
He shot more coverage?

00:32:11.200 --> 00:32:13.760
AUDIENCE: He said that to
me, I ask him a while ago.

00:32:13.760 --> 00:32:15.930
That is what he said,
is that he always felt--

00:32:15.930 --> 00:32:16.700
CARLOS MARQUES
MARCET: You met him?

00:32:16.700 --> 00:32:18.220
AUDIENCE: I worked for him.

00:32:18.220 --> 00:32:18.720
He said--

00:32:18.720 --> 00:32:21.053
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET: Now I
want to ask you a question.

00:32:21.053 --> 00:32:23.400
AUDIENCE: I was trying
not to go there.

00:32:23.400 --> 00:32:24.620
It's just, I love him too.

00:32:24.620 --> 00:32:27.040
I mean, brilliant editor.

00:32:27.040 --> 00:32:30.629
But I always felt that,
that's why I asked him.

00:32:30.629 --> 00:32:32.420
I would think as a
director your mind would

00:32:32.420 --> 00:32:36.329
be so focused on what you were
going to create that I'd think

00:32:36.329 --> 00:32:37.620
he knew exactly what he wanted.

00:32:37.620 --> 00:32:39.328
He said no, he just
made them shoot more.

00:32:39.328 --> 00:32:42.690
And you're an editor-- started
out as an editing and filming.

00:32:42.690 --> 00:32:45.240
Especially now that you have
the digital tools that he never

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:48.014
had, I would love to know what
your thoughts are on that.

00:32:48.014 --> 00:32:49.430
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
It's funny,

00:32:49.430 --> 00:32:53.260
I have a lot of of friends
who go into directing.

00:32:53.260 --> 00:32:56.310
Most of them shoot
very little coverage.

00:32:56.310 --> 00:32:58.750
I think they are more
precise on the way

00:32:58.750 --> 00:33:00.720
that they are going to use it.

00:33:00.720 --> 00:33:03.140
It's hardly that
they shoot-- I think

00:33:03.140 --> 00:33:06.620
as an editor you tend to shoot
things that you-- you do more

00:33:06.620 --> 00:33:09.890
takes until you
get the right take,

00:33:09.890 --> 00:33:13.050
and then you don't shoot
things you're not going to use.

00:33:13.050 --> 00:33:15.030
Sometimes, in coverage,
there's this idea of,

00:33:15.030 --> 00:33:18.610
let's do things just in case.

00:33:18.610 --> 00:33:20.980
Let's do all these
long master and then

00:33:20.980 --> 00:33:23.290
they discovered this angle,
and cover this angle,

00:33:23.290 --> 00:33:27.500
and cover this angle, and
then I'll decide on the post.

00:33:27.500 --> 00:33:30.650
I feel as an editor, you already
have anything in your mind,

00:33:30.650 --> 00:33:31.380
pretty much.

00:33:31.380 --> 00:33:34.670
When something new happens,
you're already thinking, OK,

00:33:34.670 --> 00:33:38.560
that new thing happened but now
I need shoot this thing here.

00:33:38.560 --> 00:33:42.910
So you're already taking
pieces as they happen, as you

00:33:42.910 --> 00:33:46.510
get surprised, too, sometimes.

00:33:46.510 --> 00:33:50.450
I think it also makes you want
to-- for example, something

00:33:50.450 --> 00:33:52.380
that influenced
me, I feel like I

00:33:52.380 --> 00:33:55.220
wouldn't have done this very
long take at the beginning

00:33:55.220 --> 00:33:57.400
if it wasn't in the beginning.

00:33:57.400 --> 00:33:59.850
As an editor you
know that a very long

00:33:59.850 --> 00:34:01.900
take in the middle of
the movie, it's probably

00:34:01.900 --> 00:34:06.290
going to go to the
bin, because you

00:34:06.290 --> 00:34:11.909
have to be a master of having
the rhythm of the whole movie

00:34:11.909 --> 00:34:16.469
on your mind in a way that
it's almost impossible.

00:34:16.469 --> 00:34:19.050
In the middle, you've
created, and then finally you

00:34:19.050 --> 00:34:21.364
end up breaking it up.

00:34:21.364 --> 00:34:22.989
But at the beginning,
you're setting up

00:34:22.989 --> 00:34:25.630
the tone of your movie.

00:34:25.630 --> 00:34:32.199
You can see as it's developing
what's going to be the theme.

00:34:32.199 --> 00:34:35.087
You don't need to compare it to
what's come before and after.

00:34:35.087 --> 00:34:36.920
I think that's another
difference, probably,

00:34:36.920 --> 00:34:38.630
or something that
makes you think a lot,

00:34:38.630 --> 00:34:42.055
is that you are very aware of
what's come before and after.

00:34:42.055 --> 00:34:44.429
I guess all directors, but
especially which as an editor,

00:34:44.429 --> 00:34:47.380
know how you make a
transition from this scene

00:34:47.380 --> 00:34:50.790
to the other scene, or on
the way of shooting it.

00:34:50.790 --> 00:34:52.974
To me, at least, an
experience with my friends

00:34:52.974 --> 00:34:58.440
is that they shoot less,
but they shoot more takes.

00:34:58.440 --> 00:35:01.397
AUDIENCE: As I said, did
you plan longer takes also

00:35:01.397 --> 00:35:03.230
because of parallels
video conferencing that

00:35:03.230 --> 00:35:04.920
was going to happen later?

00:35:04.920 --> 00:35:07.210
Because it feels the same.

00:35:07.210 --> 00:35:09.210
CARLOS MARQUES-MARCET:
There was a little game--

00:35:09.210 --> 00:35:11.390
I'm thinking of a
game of piloting

00:35:11.390 --> 00:35:13.940
the camera and the other
camera, and I always

00:35:13.940 --> 00:35:16.460
fantasize the idea of what
cameras are going to be, like,

00:35:16.460 --> 00:35:18.970
4K quality in a few years.

00:35:18.970 --> 00:35:22.406
And there's got to be
a nice rhyme in there.

00:35:22.406 --> 00:35:24.280
To me, it was important
just to be with them.

00:35:26.987 --> 00:35:28.570
We discussed a lot
with the co-writer,

00:35:28.570 --> 00:35:31.580
this is somehow a movie
between the difference

00:35:31.580 --> 00:35:34.630
of being thrown off somebody,
in the image of somebody,

00:35:34.630 --> 00:35:38.400
also the difference of a two
shot and a shot reverse shot.

00:35:38.400 --> 00:35:40.720
I shot reverse
shot, then it feels

00:35:40.720 --> 00:35:43.420
like they are in front of them,
but it's like an abstraction.

00:35:43.420 --> 00:35:47.080
And somehow, being in front of
a computer is an abstraction.

00:35:47.080 --> 00:35:50.100
We wanted to follow them so
you have any [INAUDIBLE],

00:35:50.100 --> 00:35:53.160
you don't have
any buildup thing,

00:35:53.160 --> 00:35:55.660
and you're just with
them, sitting with them

00:35:55.660 --> 00:35:58.740
and you share with
them this reality.

00:35:58.740 --> 00:36:01.660
It was not very metaphoric.

00:36:01.660 --> 00:36:04.834
I don't like too many metaphors,
but more giving a feeling.

00:36:04.834 --> 00:36:06.500
Probably the reason
for this long thing,

00:36:06.500 --> 00:36:08.310
it was not as much
the thing itself,

00:36:08.310 --> 00:36:09.490
but the moment of the cut.

00:36:13.060 --> 00:36:16.430
The moment you cut, I knew that
was going to have an effect.

00:36:16.430 --> 00:36:19.770
You're going to miss for
the rest of the movie

00:36:19.770 --> 00:36:22.150
this moment where they've
been together in space.

00:36:22.150 --> 00:36:25.380
So that was a little bit
between-- but it was also

00:36:25.380 --> 00:36:26.880
like the beginning,
the second take,

00:36:26.880 --> 00:36:29.430
when you see him
showing the apartment,

00:36:29.430 --> 00:36:34.200
obviously that was the idea of
reminding of the first scene,

00:36:34.200 --> 00:36:35.950
but somehow then there
is a cut, and then

00:36:35.950 --> 00:36:37.730
you see him in the other room.

00:36:37.730 --> 00:36:39.762
There's an abstraction in there.

00:36:39.762 --> 00:36:41.553
AUDIENCE: I really
appreciated your editing

00:36:41.553 --> 00:36:42.852
and the way it was shot.

00:36:42.852 --> 00:36:43.352
Thanks.

00:36:43.352 --> 00:36:45.977
CARLOS MARQUES MARCET: I'll ask
you questions about Robert Wise

00:36:45.977 --> 00:36:46.642
after.

